One third of amphibians are at risk of extinction, with 1,856 out of 5,743 species threatened due to habitat loss, climate change, and pollution.
Efforts to protect amphibians and reproduce them in captivity are crucial.
The decline in frog populations is alarming, with hundreds of species facing extinction.
Urbanization and agricultural development have led to the loss of salamander habitats.
Scientists warn that the rapid rate of extinction is underestimated, with over 3,000 amphibian species in danger.
Contamination from pesticides like DDT has caused hermaphroditism in frogs, contributing to population declines.
